              2
              ) and host a mainly intensive        agriculture. Fecal coliform measurements obtained bi-weekly over three years show that        concentrations in watercourses increase with animal density in the subwatersheds. Regression        analyses have allowed the assessment of animal husbandry and human influence on FC counts in        watercourses with comparable subwatersheds. The study also shows that FC point sources        located immediately upstream from the sampling stations may increase the FC median values        from 3- to 20-fold during summer (May to October) and up to more than 100-fold during winter        (November to April). Regression equations are provided as tools to assist bacterial        contamination risk management. However, these tools have many limits: they could be improved        and completed in taking into account other parameters.},
